docs.abstract: The Vikings, the Patriots, the Jaguars and the Eagles have plenty in common, but how they handled the biggest issue of the 2017 N.F.L. season ran the gamut.
docs.snippet: The Vikings, the Patriots, the Jaguars and the Eagles have plenty in common, but how they handled the biggest issue of the 2017 N.F.L. season ran the gamut.
docs.lead_paragraph: The four N.F.L. teams still playing football this weekend have much in common: high-scoring offenses, stout defenses and fans hungering for a championship.

headline.main: Four Teams Left. Four Different Approaches to the Anthem Protests.
headline.print_headline: How the Four Teams Left in the Playoffs Handled the Anthem Protests

docs.abstract: Sgt. Hugh Barry ignored his training, a prosecutor said, when he rushed to subdue a mentally ill woman, then shot her when she grabbed a baseball bat.
docs.snippet: Sgt. Hugh Barry ignored his training, a prosecutor said, when he rushed to subdue a mentally ill woman, then shot her when she grabbed a baseball bat.
docs.lead_paragraph: A New York City police sergeant who killed a mentally ill woman wielding a baseball bat ignored his training to isolate her and instead rushed to take her down, provoking the confrontation that led to her death, a prosecutor told a judge Tuesday at the opening of the officer’s trial on murder and manslaughter charges

headline.main: Was the Police Shooting of Psychotic Woman Justified? D.A. Says No
headline.print_headline: Prosecutor Says Officer Created Chaos Before Shooting Psychotic Woman

docs.abstract: It was an oddly quiet end to a season of debate over the national anthem and N.F.L. players kneeling, sitting, raising fists and making other gestures during it.
docs.snippet: It was an oddly quiet end to a season of debate over the national anthem and N.F.L. players kneeling, sitting, raising fists and making other gestures during it.
docs.lead_paragraph: On the last day of a year in which football will be remembered as much for sideline posture — and posturing — as for on-the-field play, there were fewer than 20 N.F.L. players kneeling or sitting for the national anthem, according to reports. That was about 1 percent of the league’s players, not counting some locked arms, a few hands on shoulders and at least one fist in the air.

headline.main: National Anthem Protests Sidelined by Ambiguity
headline.print_headline: The Year’s Biggest Sports Story, All but Forgotten

docs.abstract: She didn’t just fight against police brutality. She also resisted the forced destruction of black families by the state.
docs.snippet: She didn’t just fight against police brutality. She also resisted the forced destruction of black families by the state.
docs.lead_paragraph: Erica Garner, the civil rights activist and a daughter of Eric Garner, died on Saturday, two days before the New Year and in the middle of the holiday season — a time when we’re all encouraged to be with our families. It is impossible to think of her death without thinking of her father’s death, the devastation their family must feel and the ways that black families have been destroyed throughout history.

headline.main: Erica Garner and How America Destroys Black Families

docs.abstract: The retailer said it would no longer sell the shirt shown in the image, which appeared to refer to a black child as the “coolest monkey in the jungle.”
docs.snippet: The retailer said it would no longer sell the shirt shown in the image, which appeared to refer to a black child as the “coolest monkey in the jungle.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The clothing retailer H&M apologized on Monday for an image appearing in its online store that showed a black child model wearing a hooded sweatshirt that said “coolest monkey in the jungle.” The company removed the image on Monday and said it would also pull the shirt from its stores worldwide.

headline.main: H&M Apologizes for ‘Monkey’ Image Featuring Black Child
headline.print_headline: Monkey Shirt On H&M Site Raises Outcry On Internet

docs.abstract: Hillary Clinton’s cameo at the Grammys set off a debate about how far glitzy awards shows should go in needling Democrats’ favorite target.
docs.snippet: Hillary Clinton’s cameo at the Grammys set off a debate about how far glitzy awards shows should go in needling Democrats’ favorite target.
docs.lead_paragraph: Her cameo lasted less than 20 seconds. She read just one sentence from a 336-page book. But Hillary Clinton’s surprise turn at the Grammy Awards on Sunday night, narrating some of the dishy gossip about President Trump in the best seller “Fire and Fury,” set off a roiling political debate about how far glitzy awards shows should go in needling Democrats’ favorite target.

headline.main: The Resistance Has Come to Celebrity Award Shows
headline.print_headline: Celebrities Turn Awards Stages Into Soapboxes for ‘Resistance’

docs.abstract: Dean Moss’s “Petra” riffs on Fassbinder’s “Petra von Kant” and his life as a choreographer: “that process where you never attain what your desire is.”
docs.snippet: Dean Moss’s “Petra” riffs on Fassbinder’s “Petra von Kant” and his life as a choreographer: “that process where you never attain what your desire is.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Desire and power, the New York performance scene, the Hindu goddess Chinnamasta and Rainer Werner Fassbinder’s film “The Bitter Tears of Petra von Kant” are all mixed into Dean Moss’s latest performative stew, “Petra.”

headline.main: That Obscure, Unattainable Object of Desire: Your Own Art
headline.print_headline: That Elusive Object of Desire: Your Own Art
